It's fascinating to see the world change.
The fact that teenagers and children no longer go out to play but prefer to spend their free time staring at screens has been lamented by many over the past decade.
Pokemon Go is about getting people off the couch and getting more active.
Time spent on the screen was limited to the TV, then to video games, and finally to smartphones.
So it's great to see that technology and outdoor activities are not mutually exclusive.
I'm referring to the Pokémon Go delusion, of course, an app based on the characters that were originally created for video games in the 1990s (later a cartoon series, playing cards and other spin-offs).
Like many pop culture phenomena, interest dropped slightly before the game's release in the US, Australia and New Zealand in early July.
The launch in other countries was delayed by the massive demand that overwhelmed the servers.
Within days, Pokémon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as many as Twitter.
How does it work?
In short, players go out with their smartphones and search for Pokémon that can be tracked with a GPS and, once found, "photographed" (by a screenshot on their phone) or "captured".
A generation that played the game when they were younger joined the madness and jumped off the couch to find it.
In the United States, gambling led to a significant increase in the number of steps taken by the "average" person every day.
Cardiogram, an app for Apple Watch that tracks 35,000 users, recently reported to the Washington Post that within two days of the game's launch, the number of people tracked who train for 30 minutes a day jumped from 45 percent to 53 percent.
The company doesn't know who's playing Pokémon Go - it's just looking at the raw data to improve performance.
Many public health education campaigns that want people to "take 30 minutes to get off the couch", "get off the couch" and "be active every day" have been deafening because many public health messages are boring and come from people who look miserable.
Nevertheless, the importance of sport cannot be overstated.
Regular exercise reduces the chances of developing cancer or depression.
Physical activity helps with weight control, high blood pressure, diabetes, and a long list of benefits that's too long to list here.
But the wonderful thing about Pokémon Go is that it makes people do something outdoors that they enjoy.
Thus, three pillars of health are covered - exercise, fresh air, sunshine, and fun.
Some people even make new friends on the hunt.
As always, there are also the murky game-wreckers who always have to complain about something.
And yes, someone could run into a door.
What's the matter?
There's been a breakthrough.
Even though smartphone apps like Fitbit were able to track our activity earlier, they didn't give us any reason to exercise like this game does.
The new will lose its appeal and use will decline over time.
But because of Pokemon's success, there will be more games that will combine apps and virtual reality with being active in the real world, helping many people on the hunt to be more active, fitter and healthier.
