Military leadership falsifies ISIS intelligence, Congress committee finds
Military members of the United States Central Command altered intelligence to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against the so-called Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than actual conditions on the ground would have allowed, a congressional investigation committee reported in a report on Thursday.
The preliminary report, compiled by a task force of Republican members of the Armed Services Committee, Intelligence Committee, and the Armed Services Budget Committee, reports major discontent among Central Command intelligence analysts who reported how their superiors changed their assessment of American efforts in the fight against the Islamic State.
Central Command, or Cencom, is the military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, which controls U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"Intelligence information typically stolen by senior Centcom commanders regularly showed a more positive picture of American counterterrorism efforts than actual conditions on the ground would have allowed and was consistently more positive than analysis by other intelligence services", the report said.
"What happened at Centcom is unacceptable - our soldiers suffer when bad analysis is presented to our political leaders", said Ken Calvert, a Republican member of the House of Representatives.
The mistakes of the Centcom leadership extend to the top of the organization.
The 10-page report details ongoing problems in 2014 and 2015 in the description and analysis of US efforts to train Iraqi forces.
While it provides no direct evidence that Obama administration leaders have given instructions to change the reports, it shows how analysts have been exposed to pressure from their bosses to paint a more optimistic picture of the threat posed by the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
"During the first half of 2015, many Central Command press releases, statements and statements made to Congress were significantly more positive than they were", the report noted.
For example, a Centcom official publicly announced that a military retake of Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq's second largest city, remains under the control of the Islamic State.
"After months of investigation, that's all that's clear", said Mike Pompeo, a Republican congressman from Kansas, in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the Central Command's top officials changed intelligence reports to minimize the threat of ISIS in Iraq.
The Republicans launched the Task Force after they were told analysts were concerned about the manipulation of reports on the Islamic State.
The report published on Thursday will be supplemented by more detailed findings as investigations continue.
In addition, further investigations into Centcom's reports by the Inspector General of the Ministry of Defence are underway.
Democratic members of the Intelligence Committee released their own findings on Thursday, which were in line with some of the Republican Task Force's findings.
"In 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an overly restricted process for producing intelligence assessments of ISIL and Iraqi security services", said senior Democratic member of the committee, House Speaker Adam B. Schiff, in a statement.
This process, Mr. Schiff said, "delayed the publication of intelligence reports", damaged the morale of analysts, and "provided excessively little room for divergent opinions".
But Mr. Schiff and the Democrats said they found no evidence of White House interference with Centcom analysts regarding "a particular political opinion".
The preliminary findings of the congressional investigation were published Tuesday by The Daily Beast.
Last August, the New York Times reported on investigations by the Pentagon's inspector general, which were taken after complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lt. Cmdr. Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Department of Defense would not comment on any congressional reports while the inspector general's investigation is ongoing.
But he also said that "experts sometimes have quite divergent opinions on how to interpret complex data, and that the intelligence services and the Department of Defense welcome a controversial discussion of these important issues of national defense".
The investigation has implications beyond the question of a successful US-led air campaign in Iraq and Syria (a claim now made by a growing number of Defence Ministry personnel).
Last year's allegations raised the question of how much President Obama can rely on Central Command for honest assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis regions.
Criticism of the classified information about the Islamic State recalls conflicts more than a decade ago when a Centcom analyst, Gregory Hooker, wrote a paper about how the then George W. Bush administration, contrary to many analysts' recommendations, provided only a small occupation force in Iraq and spent little time thinking about the aftermath of the 2003 invasion.
Mr. Hooker also played a key role in the uprising against the current coverage of the Islamic State.
Last year, the team around Mr Hooker reported from government agencies that, contrary to government statements, airstrikes on the Islamic State-held refineries had no significant impact on the financial situation of the terrorist group, as these provisional refineries were set up to sell oil on the black market.
However, this finding was not published, the Times reported in September.
Centcom's then commander, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized by members of the legislature for his overly positive assessment of the war situation during a Senate hearing.
General Austin retired in April and was replaced at Central Command by General Joseph L. Votel.
