In the midst of the Olympic rage, the Zen of the trampoline
Wherever you are, whatever the time, it's the Olympics.
The events in Rio de Janeiro feel constant and inevitable, a racing race between competition and aspiration.
It's like the Olympic torch itself is a burning stick, handed down from the shooter to the swimmer to the athlete to the triathlete.
You can't turn on the TV, read a newspaper, or listen to your neighbor's conversation in the coffee shop queue without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the fight between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
