"A generation is protesting" in Ethiopia, Long an ally of the United States
Violent Protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia encountered violent resistance from the government.
Witnesses say dozens of protesters were killed in clashes with police in a shootout.
Is Ethiopia about to collapse?
In the last decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a solid ally of the West with a rapidly growing economy.
But in recent months, protests against the government have shaken the country and spread to more and more areas.
Last week, thousands of people took to the streets demanding fundamental political change.
Human rights groups say the government's response was ruthless.
Witnesses said police fired and killed dozens of unarmed protesters.
Videos circulating about the protests, probably from the end of this year or early this year, show security personnel beating young people with sticks as they were forced to raise their hands against a wall.
The head of the UN Human Rights Commission is now demanding a thorough investigation.
"It has always been difficult to hold this country together, and it will be even more difficult in the future", said Rashid Abdi, project manager of the Horn of Africa at the International Crisis Group, a research group.
Ethiopia is the most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is appreciated by the West.
US military and intelligence services are working closely with the Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats beyond the region, particularly in Somalia. Few countries in Africa, if any, receive so much Western aid.
Ethiopia's economy expanded at a remarkable pace.
Its infrastructure has improved dramatically - there is a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
The streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
Even though Ethiopia was anything but a model of democracy - human rights organizations have continually led the government's repression - opposition in the country has been curtailed, effectively silencing dissidents.
Many were exiled or imprisoned, killed, or driven into the vastness of the wilderness.
But that could change.
"When you oppress people and they have no choice but to protest, it breaks out", said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer in central Ethiopia.
The whole youth is protesting.
A generation of protesters.
There are numerous complaints covering everything from land use to strangulation regarding the power of the ruling coalition.
After a widely criticized election last year, the ruling party and its allies won the last seat of the opposition and now control 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea, a battle over this loose, controversial line that claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatists like the Oromo Liberation Front or Ogaden National Liberation Front, which have been more or less subdued in recent years, could take advantage of the turmoil and rearm themselves.
Several factors explain why feelings of bitterness now explode after years of quaking beneath the surface.
The first seems harmless: smartphones.
Only in recent years have many Ethiopians been able to communicate through social media as cheaper smartphones have become more common and Internet services have improved.
Even if the government blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, which it does at regular intervals, especially during protests, many people can still communicate via Internet proxies that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians reported that they had gathered in protest.
The second factor is that there is more solidarity between the Oromo and Amhara, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oromos and Amhara are not natural enemies.
For centuries, the Amhara people, who come from Ethiopia's predominantly Christian highlands, have flourished in politics and business, while exploiting the Oromos, many of whom are Muslims and live in lowlands.
But that's changing, too.
"We are coordinating under one umbrella", said Mulatu Gemechu, a leader of the Oromo.
The largest protests took place in Amhara and Oromo areas.
Many Amharians and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the ethnic group of Tigray, who make up about 6 percent of the population and are dominant in the military, intelligence, trade and politics.
The third reason for the riots is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Mr Meles, a former rebel leader, was Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death from an undisclosed illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could think around corners.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at detecting early signs of dissatisfaction and using special agents to manipulate opponents and render them harmless.
"The current regime lacks this basic skill", said Mr Abdi, a conflict analyst.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desalegn, was chosen to take the position of Mr Meles for relatively obscure reasons.
Unlike Mr Meles, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Mr Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he doesn't enjoy the trust of the security services controlled by the Tigray.
Many fear that the result will be more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such an uproar was in 2005, after thousands protested elections that analysts said were apparently rigged by the government and then stolen.
During the raids that followed, many protesters were killed, although fewer than in recent months and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia's leaders for their visionary infrastructure planning, such as the new commuter train, and for their measurable progress in fighting poverty.
But obviously this has not prevented the intensification of the internal dislike of the Ethiopian government.
And it takes on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters attacked Tigray-run businesses in Gondar, an Amharic city, and hatred of Tigray is becoming more common on social media.
Analysts say the protests are putting the United States and other Western allies in a strange position.
The US government used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, even though it recently announced it had closed down that base.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it doesn't want its ally to collapse in an already volatile area.
"This", said Mr Abdi, "is a very thin line migration".
