Kepler measures the rotation rate of stars in the pleiadian cluster
The latest mission with the Kepler Space Telescope has helped astronomers to collect the most complete catalog of rotation rates among the stars of the Pleiadian cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars rotate at different rates in the star cluster and how the rotation periods relate to the formation of the planets.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other clusters of stars, we can learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age, and even the history of its solar system", said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, in a press release.
The Pleiadian cluster is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in this cluster, which formed about 125 million years ago, are now reaching adulthood.
They're turning fastest now.
At peak rotational rates, these mature stars emit large amounts of stellar winds.
Since these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars, they have a braking effect on the stars.
As a star ages, its rotation rate begins to slow.
Kepler measures the rate of rotation of each star by identifying the time between the appearance of a noticeable star spot -- like sunspots.
The latest catalog of rotation rates suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to dancers, with larger stars rotating slowly than smaller ones.
"In the 'ballet' of the Pleiades, we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive, whereas faster rotors tend to be very bright stars", Rebull said.
Because the star cluster is so close to the Pleiades, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory for comparing stellar qualities such as rotation rates.
"The pleiadian cluster provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, younger and older", Rebull said.
We have much to learn about, such as how, when, and why stars slow down their rotation rates and hang their "dance shoes" so to speak.
Rebull and her colleagues have reported extensively in three newspaper reports on their latest analysis of the rotation rates of the pleiades, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
