In a recent study, F-Secure security researchers have examined user interfaces and contact with the blackmailers and come to the conclusion that the perpetrators are actually trying to build a kind of customer service to collect more money.
They explain to their victims via chat how to pay with bitcoin, set up freely accessible support sites, or decrypt example files for free.
And if individuals are rescued after paying a few hundred euros, companies will have to negotiate hard and pay five-digit sums to get their data back unencrypted.
Given the potentially high and relatively risk-free profits from ransomware blackmail, hackers are becoming more professional and sharing the work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski of antivirus provider Sophos: "A single person can write a ransomware in about a week".
